& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Acute chest pain is a common reason for visits to the emergency department. It is important to distinguish among the various causes of acute chest pain, because treatment and prognosis are substantially different among the various conditions. It is critical to exclude acute coronary syndrome (ACS), which is a major cause of hospitalization, death, and health care costs worldwide. Myocardial ischemia is defined as potential myocyte death secondary to an imbalance between oxygen supply and demand due to obstruction of an epicardial coronary artery. Unobstructed coronary artery disease can have cardiac causes (eg, myocarditis, myocardial infarction with nonobstructed coronary arteries, and Takotsubo cardiomyopathy), and noncardiac diseases can manifest with acute chest pain and increased serum cardiac biomarker levels. In the emergency department, cardiac MRI may aid in the identification of patients with non-ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction or unstable angina or ACS with unobstructed coronary artery disease, if the patient’s clinical history is known to be atypical. Also, cardiac MRI is excellent for risk stratification of patients for adverse left ventricular remodeling or major adverse cardiac events. Cardiac MRI should be performed early in the course of the disease (&lt;2 weeks after onset of symptoms). Steady-state free-precession T2-weighted MRI with late gadolinium enhancement is the mainstay of the cardiac MRI protocol. Further sequences can be used to analyze the different pathophysiologic subjacent mechanisms of the disease, such as microvascular obstruction or intramyocardial hemorrhage. Finally, cardiac MRI may provide several prognostic biomarkers that help in follow-up of these patients.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200084">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200084">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic" aria-label="NSTEMI in a 49-year-old woman (see also Movie 1). (a) Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows a transmural area of hyperintensity (arrow) that is 100% of the thickness of the lateral wall of the LV (T2 ratio, &gt;2), which is suggestive of myocardial edema of ischemic origin (area at risk). (b) Midventricular short-axis two-dimensional LGE MR image after optimized selection of the inversion time shows transmural (50%–75%) enhancement of the lateral wall of the LV (left circumflex artery territory) that suggests acute MI (arrow). The difference in myocardial necrosis (infarct size) and the area at risk is, by definition, the MSI (MSI = area at risk − infarct size)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig1a.jpeg" height="1208" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. NSTEMI in a 49-year-old woman (see also Movie 1). <b>(a)</b> Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows a transmural area of hyperintensity (arrow) that is 100% of the thickness of the lateral wall of the LV (T2 ratio, &gt;2), which is suggestive of myocardial edema of ischemic origin (area at risk). <b>(b)</b> Midventricular short-axis two-dimensional LGE MR image after optimized selection of the inversion time shows transmural (50%–75%) enhancement of the lateral wall of the LV (left circumflex artery territory) that suggests acute MI (arrow). The difference in myocardial necrosis (infarct size) and the area at risk is, by definition, the MSI (MSI = area at risk − infarct size).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="NSTEMI in a 49-year-old woman (see also Movie 1). (a) Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows a transmural area of hyperintensity (arrow) that is 100% of the thickness of the lateral wall of the LV (T2 ratio, &gt;2), which is suggestive of myocardial edema of ischemic origin (area at risk). (b) Midventricular short-axis two-dimensional LGE MR image after optimized selection of the inversion time shows transmural (50%–75%) enhancement of the lateral wall of the LV (left circumflex artery territory) that suggests acute MI (arrow). The difference in myocardial necrosis (infarct size) and the area at risk is, by definition, the MSI (MSI = area at risk − infarct size)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig1b.jpeg" height="1208" width="1474" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. NSTEMI in a 49-year-old woman (see also Movie 1). <b>(a)</b> Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows a transmural area of hyperintensity (arrow) that is 100% of the thickness of the lateral wall of the LV (T2 ratio, &gt;2), which is suggestive of myocardial edema of ischemic origin (area at risk). <b>(b)</b> Midventricular short-axis two-dimensional LGE MR image after optimized selection of the inversion time shows transmural (50%–75%) enhancement of the lateral wall of the LV (left circumflex artery territory) that suggests acute MI (arrow). The difference in myocardial necrosis (infarct size) and the area at risk is, by definition, the MSI (MSI = area at risk − infarct size).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Chart shows cardiac MRI techniques and their utility for assessment of various findings compared with the use of other noninvasive imaging techniques. IMH = intramyocardial hemorrhage, LVR = LV remodeling, RM = remote myocardium, VF = ventricular function."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig2.jpeg" height="1631" width="3397" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Chart shows cardiac MRI techniques and their utility for assessment of various findings compared with the use of other noninvasive imaging techniques. IMH = intramyocardial hemorrhage, LVR = LV remodeling, RM = remote myocardium, VF = ventricular function.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="Unstable angina in a 51-year-old woman with acute chest pain and elevated serum cardiac biomarker levels (see also Movie 2). (a) Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural myocardial edema in the anterior segment of the LV (arrow). (b) Midventricular short-axis MR image that was acquired during LGE shows the absence of LGE (arrow). Absence of LGE and the appropriate clinical symptoms (acute chest pain with elevated serum cardiac biomarker levels and non-ST-segment elevation at electrocardiography) are keys to differentiating NSTEMI from unstable angina."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig3a.jpeg" height="1250" width="1484" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Unstable angina in a 51-year-old woman with acute chest pain and elevated serum cardiac biomarker levels (see also Movie 2). <b>(a)</b> Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural myocardial edema in the anterior segment of the LV (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Midventricular short-axis MR image that was acquired during LGE shows the absence of LGE (arrow). Absence of LGE and the appropriate clinical symptoms (acute chest pain with elevated serum cardiac biomarker levels and non-ST-segment elevation at electrocardiography) are keys to differentiating NSTEMI from unstable angina.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="Unstable angina in a 51-year-old woman with acute chest pain and elevated serum cardiac biomarker levels (see also Movie 2). (a) Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural myocardial edema in the anterior segment of the LV (arrow). (b) Midventricular short-axis MR image that was acquired during LGE shows the absence of LGE (arrow). Absence of LGE and the appropriate clinical symptoms (acute chest pain with elevated serum cardiac biomarker levels and non-ST-segment elevation at electrocardiography) are keys to differentiating NSTEMI from unstable angina."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig3b.jpeg" height="1250" width="1466" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Unstable angina in a 51-year-old woman with acute chest pain and elevated serum cardiac biomarker levels (see also Movie 2). <b>(a)</b> Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural myocardial edema in the anterior segment of the LV (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Midventricular short-axis MR image that was acquired during LGE shows the absence of LGE (arrow). Absence of LGE and the appropriate clinical symptoms (acute chest pain with elevated serum cardiac biomarker levels and non-ST-segment elevation at electrocardiography) are keys to differentiating NSTEMI from unstable angina.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Equations show methods for quantitative calculation of the MSI."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig4.jpeg" height="2123" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Equations show methods for quantitative calculation of the MSI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic" aria-label="ACS in a 70-year-old man with no significant coronary artery disease at cardiac catheterization. Cardiac MRI was performed to exclude MINOCA. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural hyperintensity on the basal anterior and anteroseptal segments, with subendocardial linear hypointensity, which suggests myocardial edema (myocardium at risk) with MVO (thick arrow). Note the presence of a slow-flow artifact (thin arrow). (b–d) Diffusion-weighted MR images with b = 50 sec/mm2 (b) and b = 300 sec/mm2 (c) and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map (d) show hyperintensity of the anterior and septal segments at both b values, which suggests that myocardial edema is of ischemic origin. Note the high conspicuity of the altered myocardium (thick arrow) compared with the normal myocardium. Also note the absence of slow-flow artifacts (thin arrow) on the diffusion-weighted MR images and the effects of echo-planar imaging artifacts at b = 300 sec/mm2."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig5a.jpeg" height="1297" width="1126" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. ACS in a 70-year-old man with no significant coronary artery disease at cardiac catheterization. Cardiac MRI was performed to exclude MINOCA. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural hyperintensity on the basal anterior and anteroseptal segments, with subendocardial linear hypointensity, which suggests myocardial edema (myocardium at risk) with MVO (thick arrow). Note the presence of a slow-flow artifact (thin arrow). <b>(b</b>–<b>d)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR images with <i>b</i> = 50 sec/mm<sup>2</sup><b> (b)</b> and <i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup><b> (c)</b> and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map <b>(d)</b> show hyperintensity of the anterior and septal segments at both <i>b</i> values, which suggests that myocardial edema is of ischemic origin. Note the high conspicuity of the altered myocardium (thick arrow) compared with the normal myocardium. Also note the absence of slow-flow artifacts (thin arrow) on the diffusion-weighted MR images and the effects of echo-planar imaging artifacts at <i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="ACS in a 70-year-old man with no significant coronary artery disease at cardiac catheterization. Cardiac MRI was performed to exclude MINOCA. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural hyperintensity on the basal anterior and anteroseptal segments, with subendocardial linear hypointensity, which suggests myocardial edema (myocardium at risk) with MVO (thick arrow). Note the presence of a slow-flow artifact (thin arrow). (b–d) Diffusion-weighted MR images with b = 50 sec/mm2 (b) and b = 300 sec/mm2 (c) and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map (d) show hyperintensity of the anterior and septal segments at both b values, which suggests that myocardial edema is of ischemic origin. Note the high conspicuity of the altered myocardium (thick arrow) compared with the normal myocardium. Also note the absence of slow-flow artifacts (thin arrow) on the diffusion-weighted MR images and the effects of echo-planar imaging artifacts at b = 300 sec/mm2."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig5b.jpeg" height="1297" width="1124" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. ACS in a 70-year-old man with no significant coronary artery disease at cardiac catheterization. Cardiac MRI was performed to exclude MINOCA. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural hyperintensity on the basal anterior and anteroseptal segments, with subendocardial linear hypointensity, which suggests myocardial edema (myocardium at risk) with MVO (thick arrow). Note the presence of a slow-flow artifact (thin arrow). <b>(b</b>–<b>d)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR images with <i>b</i> = 50 sec/mm<sup>2</sup><b> (b)</b> and <i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup><b> (c)</b> and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map <b>(d)</b> show hyperintensity of the anterior and septal segments at both <i>b</i> values, which suggests that myocardial edema is of ischemic origin. Note the high conspicuity of the altered myocardium (thick arrow) compared with the normal myocardium. Also note the absence of slow-flow artifacts (thin arrow) on the diffusion-weighted MR images and the effects of echo-planar imaging artifacts at <i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic" aria-label="ACS in a 70-year-old man with no significant coronary artery disease at cardiac catheterization. Cardiac MRI was performed to exclude MINOCA. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural hyperintensity on the basal anterior and anteroseptal segments, with subendocardial linear hypointensity, which suggests myocardial edema (myocardium at risk) with MVO (thick arrow). Note the presence of a slow-flow artifact (thin arrow). (b–d) Diffusion-weighted MR images with b = 50 sec/mm2 (b) and b = 300 sec/mm2 (c) and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map (d) show hyperintensity of the anterior and septal segments at both b values, which suggests that myocardial edema is of ischemic origin. Note the high conspicuity of the altered myocardium (thick arrow) compared with the normal myocardium. Also note the absence of slow-flow artifacts (thin arrow) on the diffusion-weighted MR images and the effects of echo-planar imaging artifacts at b = 300 sec/mm2."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig5c.jpeg" height="1305" width="1134" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. ACS in a 70-year-old man with no significant coronary artery disease at cardiac catheterization. Cardiac MRI was performed to exclude MINOCA. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural hyperintensity on the basal anterior and anteroseptal segments, with subendocardial linear hypointensity, which suggests myocardial edema (myocardium at risk) with MVO (thick arrow). Note the presence of a slow-flow artifact (thin arrow). <b>(b</b>–<b>d)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR images with <i>b</i> = 50 sec/mm<sup>2</sup><b> (b)</b> and <i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup><b> (c)</b> and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map <b>(d)</b> show hyperintensity of the anterior and septal segments at both <i>b</i> values, which suggests that myocardial edema is of ischemic origin. Note the high conspicuity of the altered myocardium (thick arrow) compared with the normal myocardium. Also note the absence of slow-flow artifacts (thin arrow) on the diffusion-weighted MR images and the effects of echo-planar imaging artifacts at <i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic" aria-label="ACS in a 70-year-old man with no significant coronary artery disease at cardiac catheterization. Cardiac MRI was performed to exclude MINOCA. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural hyperintensity on the basal anterior and anteroseptal segments, with subendocardial linear hypointensity, which suggests myocardial edema (myocardium at risk) with MVO (thick arrow). Note the presence of a slow-flow artifact (thin arrow). (b–d) Diffusion-weighted MR images with b = 50 sec/mm2 (b) and b = 300 sec/mm2 (c) and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map (d) show hyperintensity of the anterior and septal segments at both b values, which suggests that myocardial edema is of ischemic origin. Note the high conspicuity of the altered myocardium (thick arrow) compared with the normal myocardium. Also note the absence of slow-flow artifacts (thin arrow) on the diffusion-weighted MR images and the effects of echo-planar imaging artifacts at b = 300 sec/mm2."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig5d.jpeg" height="1305" width="1116" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. ACS in a 70-year-old man with no significant coronary artery disease at cardiac catheterization. Cardiac MRI was performed to exclude MINOCA. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows transmural hyperintensity on the basal anterior and anteroseptal segments, with subendocardial linear hypointensity, which suggests myocardial edema (myocardium at risk) with MVO (thick arrow). Note the presence of a slow-flow artifact (thin arrow). <b>(b</b>–<b>d)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR images with <i>b</i> = 50 sec/mm<sup>2</sup><b> (b)</b> and <i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup><b> (c)</b> and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map <b>(d)</b> show hyperintensity of the anterior and septal segments at both <i>b</i> values, which suggests that myocardial edema is of ischemic origin. Note the high conspicuity of the altered myocardium (thick arrow) compared with the normal myocardium. Also note the absence of slow-flow artifacts (thin arrow) on the diffusion-weighted MR images and the effects of echo-planar imaging artifacts at <i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="Acute MI of the right coronary artery territory with right ventricle involvement in a 46-year-old man with atypical chest pain (see also Movie 3). T2-weighted STIR MR image (a) and MR image acquired during EGE (b) show myocardial edema (area at risk) in both the midventricular inferoseptal wall of the LV (thick arrow) and the inferior and lateral wall of the right ventricle (thin arrow). The extension of the area at risk is similar on images from both sequences."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig6a.jpeg" height="1031" width="1328" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Acute MI of the right coronary artery territory with right ventricle involvement in a 46-year-old man with atypical chest pain (see also Movie 3). T2-weighted STIR MR image <b>(a)</b> and MR image acquired during EGE <b>(b)</b> show myocardial edema (area at risk) in both the midventricular inferoseptal wall of the LV (thick arrow) and the inferior and lateral wall of the right ventricle (thin arrow). The extension of the area at risk is similar on images from both sequences.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="Acute MI of the right coronary artery territory with right ventricle involvement in a 46-year-old man with atypical chest pain (see also Movie 3). T2-weighted STIR MR image (a) and MR image acquired during EGE (b) show myocardial edema (area at risk) in both the midventricular inferoseptal wall of the LV (thick arrow) and the inferior and lateral wall of the right ventricle (thin arrow). The extension of the area at risk is similar on images from both sequences."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig6b.jpeg" height="1031" width="1326" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Acute MI of the right coronary artery territory with right ventricle involvement in a 46-year-old man with atypical chest pain (see also Movie 3). T2-weighted STIR MR image <b>(a)</b> and MR image acquired during EGE <b>(b)</b> show myocardial edema (area at risk) in both the midventricular inferoseptal wall of the LV (thick arrow) and the inferior and lateral wall of the right ventricle (thin arrow). The extension of the area at risk is similar on images from both sequences.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="Patterns of ischemic LGE in the coronary artery territory according to American Heart Association classification of the myocardial segment. (a) Illustration of the bull’s-eye shows patterns of enhancement according to coronary vessel involvement. The left anterior descending artery pattern (green) includes basal and midventricular anterior and anteroseptal segments, apical anterior, and septal segments of the LV and the apex. The left circumflex coronary artery pattern (yellow) involves the lateral wall of the LV. The right coronary artery pattern (orange) affects the inferior wall and basal and midventricular inferolateral segments of the LV. When two or three vessels are responsible for the cardiac damage, the number of involved segments may be summed. (b) Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 53-year-old man shows subendocardial enhancement involving the anterior and anteroseptal midventricular segments, which suggests an acute MI in the left anterior descending artery. (c) Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 49-year-old woman shows subendocardial enhancement of the midventricular lateral wall that suggests a left circumflex artery myocardial infarction. (d) Short-axis MR image acquired in a 46-year-old man during LGE shows transmural enhancement of the inferior midventricular segment, which is compatible with right coronary artery myocardial infarction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig7a.jpeg" height="1307" width="1216" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Patterns of ischemic LGE in the coronary artery territory according to American Heart Association classification of the myocardial segment. <b>(a)</b> Illustration of the bull’s-eye shows patterns of enhancement according to coronary vessel involvement. The left anterior descending artery pattern (green) includes basal and midventricular anterior and anteroseptal segments, apical anterior, and septal segments of the LV and the apex. The left circumflex coronary artery pattern (yellow) involves the lateral wall of the LV. The right coronary artery pattern (orange) affects the inferior wall and basal and midventricular inferolateral segments of the LV. When two or three vessels are responsible for the cardiac damage, the number of involved segments may be summed. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 53-year-old man shows subendocardial enhancement involving the anterior and anteroseptal midventricular segments, which suggests an acute MI in the left anterior descending artery. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 49-year-old woman shows subendocardial enhancement of the midventricular lateral wall that suggests a left circumflex artery myocardial infarction. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired in a 46-year-old man during LGE shows transmural enhancement of the inferior midventricular segment, which is compatible with right coronary artery myocardial infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="Patterns of ischemic LGE in the coronary artery territory according to American Heart Association classification of the myocardial segment. (a) Illustration of the bull’s-eye shows patterns of enhancement according to coronary vessel involvement. The left anterior descending artery pattern (green) includes basal and midventricular anterior and anteroseptal segments, apical anterior, and septal segments of the LV and the apex. The left circumflex coronary artery pattern (yellow) involves the lateral wall of the LV. The right coronary artery pattern (orange) affects the inferior wall and basal and midventricular inferolateral segments of the LV. When two or three vessels are responsible for the cardiac damage, the number of involved segments may be summed. (b) Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 53-year-old man shows subendocardial enhancement involving the anterior and anteroseptal midventricular segments, which suggests an acute MI in the left anterior descending artery. (c) Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 49-year-old woman shows subendocardial enhancement of the midventricular lateral wall that suggests a left circumflex artery myocardial infarction. (d) Short-axis MR image acquired in a 46-year-old man during LGE shows transmural enhancement of the inferior midventricular segment, which is compatible with right coronary artery myocardial infarction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig7b.jpeg" height="1307" width="1436" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Patterns of ischemic LGE in the coronary artery territory according to American Heart Association classification of the myocardial segment. <b>(a)</b> Illustration of the bull’s-eye shows patterns of enhancement according to coronary vessel involvement. The left anterior descending artery pattern (green) includes basal and midventricular anterior and anteroseptal segments, apical anterior, and septal segments of the LV and the apex. The left circumflex coronary artery pattern (yellow) involves the lateral wall of the LV. The right coronary artery pattern (orange) affects the inferior wall and basal and midventricular inferolateral segments of the LV. When two or three vessels are responsible for the cardiac damage, the number of involved segments may be summed. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 53-year-old man shows subendocardial enhancement involving the anterior and anteroseptal midventricular segments, which suggests an acute MI in the left anterior descending artery. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 49-year-old woman shows subendocardial enhancement of the midventricular lateral wall that suggests a left circumflex artery myocardial infarction. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired in a 46-year-old man during LGE shows transmural enhancement of the inferior midventricular segment, which is compatible with right coronary artery myocardial infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic" aria-label="Patterns of ischemic LGE in the coronary artery territory according to American Heart Association classification of the myocardial segment. (a) Illustration of the bull’s-eye shows patterns of enhancement according to coronary vessel involvement. The left anterior descending artery pattern (green) includes basal and midventricular anterior and anteroseptal segments, apical anterior, and septal segments of the LV and the apex. The left circumflex coronary artery pattern (yellow) involves the lateral wall of the LV. The right coronary artery pattern (orange) affects the inferior wall and basal and midventricular inferolateral segments of the LV. When two or three vessels are responsible for the cardiac damage, the number of involved segments may be summed. (b) Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 53-year-old man shows subendocardial enhancement involving the anterior and anteroseptal midventricular segments, which suggests an acute MI in the left anterior descending artery. (c) Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 49-year-old woman shows subendocardial enhancement of the midventricular lateral wall that suggests a left circumflex artery myocardial infarction. (d) Short-axis MR image acquired in a 46-year-old man during LGE shows transmural enhancement of the inferior midventricular segment, which is compatible with right coronary artery myocardial infarction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig7c.jpeg" height="1339" width="1499" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Patterns of ischemic LGE in the coronary artery territory according to American Heart Association classification of the myocardial segment. <b>(a)</b> Illustration of the bull’s-eye shows patterns of enhancement according to coronary vessel involvement. The left anterior descending artery pattern (green) includes basal and midventricular anterior and anteroseptal segments, apical anterior, and septal segments of the LV and the apex. The left circumflex coronary artery pattern (yellow) involves the lateral wall of the LV. The right coronary artery pattern (orange) affects the inferior wall and basal and midventricular inferolateral segments of the LV. When two or three vessels are responsible for the cardiac damage, the number of involved segments may be summed. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 53-year-old man shows subendocardial enhancement involving the anterior and anteroseptal midventricular segments, which suggests an acute MI in the left anterior descending artery. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 49-year-old woman shows subendocardial enhancement of the midventricular lateral wall that suggests a left circumflex artery myocardial infarction. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired in a 46-year-old man during LGE shows transmural enhancement of the inferior midventricular segment, which is compatible with right coronary artery myocardial infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic" aria-label="Patterns of ischemic LGE in the coronary artery territory according to American Heart Association classification of the myocardial segment. (a) Illustration of the bull’s-eye shows patterns of enhancement according to coronary vessel involvement. The left anterior descending artery pattern (green) includes basal and midventricular anterior and anteroseptal segments, apical anterior, and septal segments of the LV and the apex. The left circumflex coronary artery pattern (yellow) involves the lateral wall of the LV. The right coronary artery pattern (orange) affects the inferior wall and basal and midventricular inferolateral segments of the LV. When two or three vessels are responsible for the cardiac damage, the number of involved segments may be summed. (b) Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 53-year-old man shows subendocardial enhancement involving the anterior and anteroseptal midventricular segments, which suggests an acute MI in the left anterior descending artery. (c) Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 49-year-old woman shows subendocardial enhancement of the midventricular lateral wall that suggests a left circumflex artery myocardial infarction. (d) Short-axis MR image acquired in a 46-year-old man during LGE shows transmural enhancement of the inferior midventricular segment, which is compatible with right coronary artery myocardial infarction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig7d.jpeg" height="1339" width="1451" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Patterns of ischemic LGE in the coronary artery territory according to American Heart Association classification of the myocardial segment. <b>(a)</b> Illustration of the bull’s-eye shows patterns of enhancement according to coronary vessel involvement. The left anterior descending artery pattern (green) includes basal and midventricular anterior and anteroseptal segments, apical anterior, and septal segments of the LV and the apex. The left circumflex coronary artery pattern (yellow) involves the lateral wall of the LV. The right coronary artery pattern (orange) affects the inferior wall and basal and midventricular inferolateral segments of the LV. When two or three vessels are responsible for the cardiac damage, the number of involved segments may be summed. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 53-year-old man shows subendocardial enhancement involving the anterior and anteroseptal midventricular segments, which suggests an acute MI in the left anterior descending artery. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired during LGE in a 49-year-old woman shows subendocardial enhancement of the midventricular lateral wall that suggests a left circumflex artery myocardial infarction. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis MR image acquired in a 46-year-old man during LGE shows transmural enhancement of the inferior midventricular segment, which is compatible with right coronary artery myocardial infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustration shows assessment of the peri-infarct area (the “gray zone”) with cardiac MRI with conventional and nonenhanced and contrast-enhanced parametric T1 mapping techniques. Conventional images (acute T2-weighted [T2WI] MR images and LGE MR images) show the relationship of the area at risk (AAR) and infarct size. With T1 mapping and extracellular volume (ECV) mapping, further differentiation of the peri-infarct gray zone (green) from the true necrotic myocardium (red) and area at risk (yellow) is available. This gray zone is included on the acute LGE MR image, and this results in overestimation of the infarct size."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig8.jpeg" height="1294" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Illustration shows assessment of the peri-infarct area (the “gray zone”) with cardiac MRI with conventional and nonenhanced and contrast-enhanced parametric T1 mapping techniques. Conventional images (acute T2-weighted <i>[T2WI]</i> MR images and LGE MR images) show the relationship of the area at risk <i>(AAR)</i> and infarct size. With T1 mapping and extracellular volume <i>(ECV)</i> mapping, further differentiation of the peri-infarct gray zone (green) from the true necrotic myocardium (red) and area at risk (yellow) is available. This gray zone is included on the acute LGE MR image, and this results in overestimation of the infarct size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="NSTEMI in the left circumflex artery territory in a 49-year-old woman with acute chest pain (same patient as in Fig 1 and Movie 1). Images show the differences between semiquantitative and parametric calculation of MSI. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows edema (area at risk) involving 39% of the LV mass (arrow). (b) Semiquantitative LGE MR image with full width at half maximum technique shows myocardial necrosis in 8% of the LV mass (arrow). The MSI in this patient was 79%. The existing difference in the transmurality and extension of the T2-weighted STIR hyperintensity and LGE corresponds to potentially salvageable myocardium. (c–d) Short-axis T1 maps (modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery, native T1 mapping) acquired before (c) and after (d) administration of gadolinium contrast material show marked differences in the transmurality of reversible myocardial damage at native T1-weighted MRI (arrow in c) compared with irreversible myocardial tissue (arrow in d). This can be used to calculate the MSI."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig9a.jpeg" height="1169" width="1478" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. NSTEMI in the left circumflex artery territory in a 49-year-old woman with acute chest pain (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Fig 1</a> and Movie 1). Images show the differences between semiquantitative and parametric calculation of MSI. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows edema (area at risk) involving 39% of the LV mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Semiquantitative LGE MR image with full width at half maximum technique shows myocardial necrosis in 8% of the LV mass (arrow). The MSI in this patient was 79%. The existing difference in the transmurality and extension of the T2-weighted STIR hyperintensity and LGE corresponds to potentially salvageable myocardium. <b>(c</b>–<b>d)</b> Short-axis T1 maps (modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery, native T1 mapping) acquired before <b>(c)</b> and after <b>(d)</b> administration of gadolinium contrast material show marked differences in the transmurality of reversible myocardial damage at native T1-weighted MRI (arrow in <b>c</b>) compared with irreversible myocardial tissue (arrow in <b>d</b>). This can be used to calculate the MSI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="NSTEMI in the left circumflex artery territory in a 49-year-old woman with acute chest pain (same patient as in Fig 1 and Movie 1). Images show the differences between semiquantitative and parametric calculation of MSI. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows edema (area at risk) involving 39% of the LV mass (arrow). (b) Semiquantitative LGE MR image with full width at half maximum technique shows myocardial necrosis in 8% of the LV mass (arrow). The MSI in this patient was 79%. The existing difference in the transmurality and extension of the T2-weighted STIR hyperintensity and LGE corresponds to potentially salvageable myocardium. (c–d) Short-axis T1 maps (modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery, native T1 mapping) acquired before (c) and after (d) administration of gadolinium contrast material show marked differences in the transmurality of reversible myocardial damage at native T1-weighted MRI (arrow in c) compared with irreversible myocardial tissue (arrow in d). This can be used to calculate the MSI."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig9b.jpeg" height="1169" width="1471" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. NSTEMI in the left circumflex artery territory in a 49-year-old woman with acute chest pain (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Fig 1</a> and Movie 1). Images show the differences between semiquantitative and parametric calculation of MSI. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows edema (area at risk) involving 39% of the LV mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Semiquantitative LGE MR image with full width at half maximum technique shows myocardial necrosis in 8% of the LV mass (arrow). The MSI in this patient was 79%. The existing difference in the transmurality and extension of the T2-weighted STIR hyperintensity and LGE corresponds to potentially salvageable myocardium. <b>(c</b>–<b>d)</b> Short-axis T1 maps (modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery, native T1 mapping) acquired before <b>(c)</b> and after <b>(d)</b> administration of gadolinium contrast material show marked differences in the transmurality of reversible myocardial damage at native T1-weighted MRI (arrow in <b>c</b>) compared with irreversible myocardial tissue (arrow in <b>d</b>). This can be used to calculate the MSI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic" aria-label="NSTEMI in the left circumflex artery territory in a 49-year-old woman with acute chest pain (same patient as in Fig 1 and Movie 1). Images show the differences between semiquantitative and parametric calculation of MSI. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows edema (area at risk) involving 39% of the LV mass (arrow). (b) Semiquantitative LGE MR image with full width at half maximum technique shows myocardial necrosis in 8% of the LV mass (arrow). The MSI in this patient was 79%. The existing difference in the transmurality and extension of the T2-weighted STIR hyperintensity and LGE corresponds to potentially salvageable myocardium. (c–d) Short-axis T1 maps (modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery, native T1 mapping) acquired before (c) and after (d) administration of gadolinium contrast material show marked differences in the transmurality of reversible myocardial damage at native T1-weighted MRI (arrow in c) compared with irreversible myocardial tissue (arrow in d). This can be used to calculate the MSI."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig9c.jpeg" height="1164" width="1481" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. NSTEMI in the left circumflex artery territory in a 49-year-old woman with acute chest pain (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Fig 1</a> and Movie 1). Images show the differences between semiquantitative and parametric calculation of MSI. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows edema (area at risk) involving 39% of the LV mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Semiquantitative LGE MR image with full width at half maximum technique shows myocardial necrosis in 8% of the LV mass (arrow). The MSI in this patient was 79%. The existing difference in the transmurality and extension of the T2-weighted STIR hyperintensity and LGE corresponds to potentially salvageable myocardium. <b>(c</b>–<b>d)</b> Short-axis T1 maps (modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery, native T1 mapping) acquired before <b>(c)</b> and after <b>(d)</b> administration of gadolinium contrast material show marked differences in the transmurality of reversible myocardial damage at native T1-weighted MRI (arrow in <b>c</b>) compared with irreversible myocardial tissue (arrow in <b>d</b>). This can be used to calculate the MSI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic" aria-label="NSTEMI in the left circumflex artery territory in a 49-year-old woman with acute chest pain (same patient as in Fig 1 and Movie 1). Images show the differences between semiquantitative and parametric calculation of MSI. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows edema (area at risk) involving 39% of the LV mass (arrow). (b) Semiquantitative LGE MR image with full width at half maximum technique shows myocardial necrosis in 8% of the LV mass (arrow). The MSI in this patient was 79%. The existing difference in the transmurality and extension of the T2-weighted STIR hyperintensity and LGE corresponds to potentially salvageable myocardium. (c–d) Short-axis T1 maps (modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery, native T1 mapping) acquired before (c) and after (d) administration of gadolinium contrast material show marked differences in the transmurality of reversible myocardial damage at native T1-weighted MRI (arrow in c) compared with irreversible myocardial tissue (arrow in d). This can be used to calculate the MSI."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig9d.jpeg" height="1164" width="1468" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. NSTEMI in the left circumflex artery territory in a 49-year-old woman with acute chest pain (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Fig 1</a> and Movie 1). Images show the differences between semiquantitative and parametric calculation of MSI. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows edema (area at risk) involving 39% of the LV mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Semiquantitative LGE MR image with full width at half maximum technique shows myocardial necrosis in 8% of the LV mass (arrow). The MSI in this patient was 79%. The existing difference in the transmurality and extension of the T2-weighted STIR hyperintensity and LGE corresponds to potentially salvageable myocardium. <b>(c</b>–<b>d)</b> Short-axis T1 maps (modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery, native T1 mapping) acquired before <b>(c)</b> and after <b>(d)</b> administration of gadolinium contrast material show marked differences in the transmurality of reversible myocardial damage at native T1-weighted MRI (arrow in <b>c</b>) compared with irreversible myocardial tissue (arrow in <b>d</b>). This can be used to calculate the MSI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic" aria-label="Acute STEMI secondary to acute occlusion of the right coronary artery in a 49-year-old man (same patient as in Movie 4) with partial recanalization after stent placement. (a) Midventricular short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement with 25%–50% transmurality in the right coronary artery territory (infarct size, region 3), with mild peri-infarct enhancement that suggests an edematous myocardium (area at risk, region 2). Notice the marked difference in signal intensity of regions 2 and 3 compared with that of the remote myocardium (region 1). (b) Gradient spin-echo T2 map shows pronounced differences in signal intensity among the remote myocardium (region 1; T2 value, 53.9 msec ± 119), the myocardium at risk (region 2; T2 value, 67.7 msec ± 4.58), and the necrotic myocardium (region 3; T2 value, 55.3 msec ± 3.56). (c, d) Nonenhanced (native T1) (c) and gadolinium-enhanced (contrast-enhanced T1) (d) short-axis midventricular T1 maps (MOLLI) also show substantial differences among the remote myocardium (native T1 value, 1150 msec ± 119; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 410 msec ± 20.8; extracellular volume, 31.7%; region 1), the myocardium at risk (native T1 value, 1202 msec ± 38.4; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 300 msec ± 116; extracellular volume, 50.5%; region 2), and the myocardial scar (native T1 value, 1095 msec ± 233; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 229 msec ± 18.3; extracellular volume, 69.8%; region 3). The correct identification of the gray zone is important because it could be the source of reentry arrhythmias in patients with acute MI."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig10a.jpeg" height="1240" width="1331" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Acute STEMI secondary to acute occlusion of the right coronary artery in a 49-year-old man (same patient as in Movie 4) with partial recanalization after stent placement. <b>(a)</b> Midventricular short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement with 25%–50% transmurality in the right coronary artery territory (infarct size, region <i>3</i>), with mild peri-infarct enhancement that suggests an edematous myocardium (area at risk, region <i>2</i>). Notice the marked difference in signal intensity of regions <i>2</i> and <i>3</i> compared with that of the remote myocardium (region <i>1</i>). <b>(b)</b> Gradient spin-echo T2 map shows pronounced differences in signal intensity among the remote myocardium (region <i>1</i>; T2 value, 53.9 msec ± 119), the myocardium at risk (region <i>2</i>; T2 value, 67.7 msec ± 4.58), and the necrotic myocardium (region <i>3</i>; T2 value, 55.3 msec ± 3.56). <b>(c, d)</b> Nonenhanced (native T1) <b>(c)</b> and gadolinium-enhanced (contrast-enhanced T1) <b>(d)</b> short-axis midventricular T1 maps (MOLLI) also show substantial differences among the remote myocardium (native T1 value, 1150 msec ± 119; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 410 msec ± 20.8; extracellular volume, 31.7%; region <i>1</i>), the myocardium at risk (native T1 value, 1202 msec ± 38.4; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 300 msec ± 116; extracellular volume, 50.5%; region <i>2</i>), and the myocardial scar (native T1 value, 1095 msec ± 233; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 229 msec ± 18.3; extracellular volume, 69.8%; region <i>3</i>). The correct identification of the gray zone is important because it could be the source of reentry arrhythmias in patients with acute MI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="Acute STEMI secondary to acute occlusion of the right coronary artery in a 49-year-old man (same patient as in Movie 4) with partial recanalization after stent placement. (a) Midventricular short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement with 25%–50% transmurality in the right coronary artery territory (infarct size, region 3), with mild peri-infarct enhancement that suggests an edematous myocardium (area at risk, region 2). Notice the marked difference in signal intensity of regions 2 and 3 compared with that of the remote myocardium (region 1). (b) Gradient spin-echo T2 map shows pronounced differences in signal intensity among the remote myocardium (region 1; T2 value, 53.9 msec ± 119), the myocardium at risk (region 2; T2 value, 67.7 msec ± 4.58), and the necrotic myocardium (region 3; T2 value, 55.3 msec ± 3.56). (c, d) Nonenhanced (native T1) (c) and gadolinium-enhanced (contrast-enhanced T1) (d) short-axis midventricular T1 maps (MOLLI) also show substantial differences among the remote myocardium (native T1 value, 1150 msec ± 119; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 410 msec ± 20.8; extracellular volume, 31.7%; region 1), the myocardium at risk (native T1 value, 1202 msec ± 38.4; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 300 msec ± 116; extracellular volume, 50.5%; region 2), and the myocardial scar (native T1 value, 1095 msec ± 233; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 229 msec ± 18.3; extracellular volume, 69.8%; region 3). The correct identification of the gray zone is important because it could be the source of reentry arrhythmias in patients with acute MI."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig10b.jpeg" height="1240" width="1318" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Acute STEMI secondary to acute occlusion of the right coronary artery in a 49-year-old man (same patient as in Movie 4) with partial recanalization after stent placement. <b>(a)</b> Midventricular short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement with 25%–50% transmurality in the right coronary artery territory (infarct size, region <i>3</i>), with mild peri-infarct enhancement that suggests an edematous myocardium (area at risk, region <i>2</i>). Notice the marked difference in signal intensity of regions <i>2</i> and <i>3</i> compared with that of the remote myocardium (region <i>1</i>). <b>(b)</b> Gradient spin-echo T2 map shows pronounced differences in signal intensity among the remote myocardium (region <i>1</i>; T2 value, 53.9 msec ± 119), the myocardium at risk (region <i>2</i>; T2 value, 67.7 msec ± 4.58), and the necrotic myocardium (region <i>3</i>; T2 value, 55.3 msec ± 3.56). <b>(c, d)</b> Nonenhanced (native T1) <b>(c)</b> and gadolinium-enhanced (contrast-enhanced T1) <b>(d)</b> short-axis midventricular T1 maps (MOLLI) also show substantial differences among the remote myocardium (native T1 value, 1150 msec ± 119; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 410 msec ± 20.8; extracellular volume, 31.7%; region <i>1</i>), the myocardium at risk (native T1 value, 1202 msec ± 38.4; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 300 msec ± 116; extracellular volume, 50.5%; region <i>2</i>), and the myocardial scar (native T1 value, 1095 msec ± 233; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 229 msec ± 18.3; extracellular volume, 69.8%; region <i>3</i>). The correct identification of the gray zone is important because it could be the source of reentry arrhythmias in patients with acute MI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic" aria-label="Acute STEMI secondary to acute occlusion of the right coronary artery in a 49-year-old man (same patient as in Movie 4) with partial recanalization after stent placement. (a) Midventricular short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement with 25%–50% transmurality in the right coronary artery territory (infarct size, region 3), with mild peri-infarct enhancement that suggests an edematous myocardium (area at risk, region 2). Notice the marked difference in signal intensity of regions 2 and 3 compared with that of the remote myocardium (region 1). (b) Gradient spin-echo T2 map shows pronounced differences in signal intensity among the remote myocardium (region 1; T2 value, 53.9 msec ± 119), the myocardium at risk (region 2; T2 value, 67.7 msec ± 4.58), and the necrotic myocardium (region 3; T2 value, 55.3 msec ± 3.56). (c, d) Nonenhanced (native T1) (c) and gadolinium-enhanced (contrast-enhanced T1) (d) short-axis midventricular T1 maps (MOLLI) also show substantial differences among the remote myocardium (native T1 value, 1150 msec ± 119; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 410 msec ± 20.8; extracellular volume, 31.7%; region 1), the myocardium at risk (native T1 value, 1202 msec ± 38.4; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 300 msec ± 116; extracellular volume, 50.5%; region 2), and the myocardial scar (native T1 value, 1095 msec ± 233; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 229 msec ± 18.3; extracellular volume, 69.8%; region 3). The correct identification of the gray zone is important because it could be the source of reentry arrhythmias in patients with acute MI."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig10c.jpeg" height="1242" width="1322" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Acute STEMI secondary to acute occlusion of the right coronary artery in a 49-year-old man (same patient as in Movie 4) with partial recanalization after stent placement. <b>(a)</b> Midventricular short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement with 25%–50% transmurality in the right coronary artery territory (infarct size, region <i>3</i>), with mild peri-infarct enhancement that suggests an edematous myocardium (area at risk, region <i>2</i>). Notice the marked difference in signal intensity of regions <i>2</i> and <i>3</i> compared with that of the remote myocardium (region <i>1</i>). <b>(b)</b> Gradient spin-echo T2 map shows pronounced differences in signal intensity among the remote myocardium (region <i>1</i>; T2 value, 53.9 msec ± 119), the myocardium at risk (region <i>2</i>; T2 value, 67.7 msec ± 4.58), and the necrotic myocardium (region <i>3</i>; T2 value, 55.3 msec ± 3.56). <b>(c, d)</b> Nonenhanced (native T1) <b>(c)</b> and gadolinium-enhanced (contrast-enhanced T1) <b>(d)</b> short-axis midventricular T1 maps (MOLLI) also show substantial differences among the remote myocardium (native T1 value, 1150 msec ± 119; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 410 msec ± 20.8; extracellular volume, 31.7%; region <i>1</i>), the myocardium at risk (native T1 value, 1202 msec ± 38.4; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 300 msec ± 116; extracellular volume, 50.5%; region <i>2</i>), and the myocardial scar (native T1 value, 1095 msec ± 233; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 229 msec ± 18.3; extracellular volume, 69.8%; region <i>3</i>). The correct identification of the gray zone is important because it could be the source of reentry arrhythmias in patients with acute MI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic" aria-label="Acute STEMI secondary to acute occlusion of the right coronary artery in a 49-year-old man (same patient as in Movie 4) with partial recanalization after stent placement. (a) Midventricular short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement with 25%–50% transmurality in the right coronary artery territory (infarct size, region 3), with mild peri-infarct enhancement that suggests an edematous myocardium (area at risk, region 2). Notice the marked difference in signal intensity of regions 2 and 3 compared with that of the remote myocardium (region 1). (b) Gradient spin-echo T2 map shows pronounced differences in signal intensity among the remote myocardium (region 1; T2 value, 53.9 msec ± 119), the myocardium at risk (region 2; T2 value, 67.7 msec ± 4.58), and the necrotic myocardium (region 3; T2 value, 55.3 msec ± 3.56). (c, d) Nonenhanced (native T1) (c) and gadolinium-enhanced (contrast-enhanced T1) (d) short-axis midventricular T1 maps (MOLLI) also show substantial differences among the remote myocardium (native T1 value, 1150 msec ± 119; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 410 msec ± 20.8; extracellular volume, 31.7%; region 1), the myocardium at risk (native T1 value, 1202 msec ± 38.4; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 300 msec ± 116; extracellular volume, 50.5%; region 2), and the myocardial scar (native T1 value, 1095 msec ± 233; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 229 msec ± 18.3; extracellular volume, 69.8%; region 3). The correct identification of the gray zone is important because it could be the source of reentry arrhythmias in patients with acute MI."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig10d.jpeg" height="1242" width="1328" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span>. Acute STEMI secondary to acute occlusion of the right coronary artery in a 49-year-old man (same patient as in Movie 4) with partial recanalization after stent placement. <b>(a)</b> Midventricular short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement with 25%–50% transmurality in the right coronary artery territory (infarct size, region <i>3</i>), with mild peri-infarct enhancement that suggests an edematous myocardium (area at risk, region <i>2</i>). Notice the marked difference in signal intensity of regions <i>2</i> and <i>3</i> compared with that of the remote myocardium (region <i>1</i>). <b>(b)</b> Gradient spin-echo T2 map shows pronounced differences in signal intensity among the remote myocardium (region <i>1</i>; T2 value, 53.9 msec ± 119), the myocardium at risk (region <i>2</i>; T2 value, 67.7 msec ± 4.58), and the necrotic myocardium (region <i>3</i>; T2 value, 55.3 msec ± 3.56). <b>(c, d)</b> Nonenhanced (native T1) <b>(c)</b> and gadolinium-enhanced (contrast-enhanced T1) <b>(d)</b> short-axis midventricular T1 maps (MOLLI) also show substantial differences among the remote myocardium (native T1 value, 1150 msec ± 119; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 410 msec ± 20.8; extracellular volume, 31.7%; region <i>1</i>), the myocardium at risk (native T1 value, 1202 msec ± 38.4; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 300 msec ± 116; extracellular volume, 50.5%; region <i>2</i>), and the myocardial scar (native T1 value, 1095 msec ± 233; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 229 msec ± 18.3; extracellular volume, 69.8%; region <i>3</i>). The correct identification of the gray zone is important because it could be the source of reentry arrhythmias in patients with acute MI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic" aria-label="Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). (b) EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. (c) LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). (d, e) Native nonenhanced (d) and contrast-enhanced (e) T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). (f, g) Both T2-weighted (f) and T2*-weighted (g) maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig11a.jpeg" height="1127" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). <b>(b)</b> EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. <b>(c)</b> LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> Native nonenhanced <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(e)</b> T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). <b>(f, g)</b> Both T2-weighted <b>(f)</b> and T2*-weighted <b>(g)</b> maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic" aria-label="Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). (b) EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. (c) LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). (d, e) Native nonenhanced (d) and contrast-enhanced (e) T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). (f, g) Both T2-weighted (f) and T2*-weighted (g) maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig11b.jpeg" height="1195" width="1180" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). <b>(b)</b> EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. <b>(c)</b> LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> Native nonenhanced <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(e)</b> T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). <b>(f, g)</b> Both T2-weighted <b>(f)</b> and T2*-weighted <b>(g)</b> maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic" aria-label="Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). (b) EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. (c) LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). (d, e) Native nonenhanced (d) and contrast-enhanced (e) T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). (f, g) Both T2-weighted (f) and T2*-weighted (g) maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig11c.jpeg" height="1195" width="1293" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). <b>(b)</b> EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. <b>(c)</b> LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> Native nonenhanced <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(e)</b> T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). <b>(f, g)</b> Both T2-weighted <b>(f)</b> and T2*-weighted <b>(g)</b> maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class