d STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). <b>(b)</b> EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. <b>(c)</b> LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> Native nonenhanced <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(e)</b> T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). <b>(f, g)</b> Both T2-weighted <b>(f)</b> and T2*-weighted <b>(g)</b> maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11e" class="graphic" aria-label="Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). (b) EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. (c) LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). (d, e) Native nonenhanced (d) and contrast-enhanced (e) T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). (f, g) Both T2-weighted (f) and T2*-weighted (g) maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig11e.jpeg" height="1171" width="1204" aria-labelledby="fig11e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11e</span>. Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). <b>(b)</b> EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. <b>(c)</b> LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> Native nonenhanced <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(e)</b> T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). <b>(f, g)</b> Both T2-weighted <b>(f)</b> and T2*-weighted <b>(g)</b> maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig11e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11f" class="graphic" aria-label="Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). (b) EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. (c) LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). (d, e) Native nonenhanced (d) and contrast-enhanced (e) T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). (f, g) Both T2-weighted (f) and T2*-weighted (g) maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig11f.jpeg" height="1171" width="1269" aria-labelledby="fig11f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11f</span>. Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). <b>(b)</b> EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. <b>(c)</b> LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> Native nonenhanced <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(e)</b> T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). <b>(f, g)</b> Both T2-weighted <b>(f)</b> and T2*-weighted <b>(g)</b> maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig11f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11g" class="graphic" aria-label="Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). (b) EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. (c) LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). (d, e) Native nonenhanced (d) and contrast-enhanced (e) T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). (f, g) Both T2-weighted (f) and T2*-weighted (g) maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig11g.jpeg" height="1171" width="1225" aria-labelledby="fig11g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11g</span>. Conventional and parametric cardiac MRI sequences in a 55-year-old man with a previous acute MI in the right coronary artery territory. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The hyperintense myocardium surrounding the MVO usually corresponds to an ischemic and infarcted myocardium (area at risk). <b>(b)</b> EGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (arrow). The necrotic myocardium may be seen as slightly hyperintense, and the normal myocardium shows intermediate signal intensity. EGE and first-pass perfusion MRI are the most sensitive sequences for showing MVO. <b>(c)</b> LGE MR image shows MVO as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial line (thick arrow) surrounded by the enhancing hyperintense necrotic myocardium (thin arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> Native nonenhanced <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(e)</b> T1 maps show the MVO with reduced native T1 and enhanced T1 values because of the T1-shortening effect of methemoglobin (arrow). <b>(f, g)</b> Both T2-weighted <b>(f)</b> and T2*-weighted <b>(g)</b> maps show the MVO (arrow) and intramyocardial hemorrhage as a hypointense subendocardial or midmyocardial region. A surrounding area of increased T2 and T2* values may be identified, indicating that the myocardium is at risk. T2*-weighted MRI also helps to identify hemoglobin degradation products.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig11g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="Remote analysis of the myocardium with LGE MRI and T1 mapping in a 45-year-old man with acute MI in the left anterior descending coronary artery territory. (a) Short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement of the anterior wall, with transmurality of 50%–75%, the necrotic myocardium (thick arrow), and the remote myocardium (thin arrow). (b) Short-axis native (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) T1 maps show the dramatic differences in the behavior between the necrotic myocardium (thick arrow) (native T1 value, 1508 msec ± 75.3; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 437 msec ± 40.1; extracellular volume, 57.1%) and the remote myocardium (thin arrow) (native T1 value, 1236 msec ± 21.7; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 600 msec ± 17.6; extracellular volume, 30.2%) in both sequences. Altered T1 mapping values are also shown in the remote myocardium, indicating a poor prognosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig12a.jpeg" height="1039" width="1242" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Remote analysis of the myocardium with LGE MRI and T1 mapping in a 45-year-old man with acute MI in the left anterior descending coronary artery territory. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement of the anterior wall, with transmurality of 50%–75%, the necrotic myocardium (thick arrow), and the remote myocardium (thin arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis native (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) T1 maps show the dramatic differences in the behavior between the necrotic myocardium (thick arrow) (native T1 value, 1508 msec ± 75.3; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 437 msec ± 40.1; extracellular volume, 57.1%) and the remote myocardium (thin arrow) (native T1 value, 1236 msec ± 21.7; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 600 msec ± 17.6; extracellular volume, 30.2%) in both sequences. Altered T1 mapping values are also shown in the remote myocardium, indicating a poor prognosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Remote analysis of the myocardium with LGE MRI and T1 mapping in a 45-year-old man with acute MI in the left anterior descending coronary artery territory. (a) Short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement of the anterior wall, with transmurality of 50%–75%, the necrotic myocardium (thick arrow), and the remote myocardium (thin arrow). (b) Short-axis native (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) T1 maps show the dramatic differences in the behavior between the necrotic myocardium (thick arrow) (native T1 value, 1508 msec ± 75.3; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 437 msec ± 40.1; extracellular volume, 57.1%) and the remote myocardium (thin arrow) (native T1 value, 1236 msec ± 21.7; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 600 msec ± 17.6; extracellular volume, 30.2%) in both sequences. Altered T1 mapping values are also shown in the remote myocardium, indicating a poor prognosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig12b.jpeg" height="1039" width="2506" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Remote analysis of the myocardium with LGE MRI and T1 mapping in a 45-year-old man with acute MI in the left anterior descending coronary artery territory. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis LGE MR image shows subendocardial enhancement of the anterior wall, with transmurality of 50%–75%, the necrotic myocardium (thick arrow), and the remote myocardium (thin arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis native (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) T1 maps show the dramatic differences in the behavior between the necrotic myocardium (thick arrow) (native T1 value, 1508 msec ± 75.3; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 437 msec ± 40.1; extracellular volume, 57.1%) and the remote myocardium (thin arrow) (native T1 value, 1236 msec ± 21.7; contrast-enhanced T1 value, 600 msec ± 17.6; extracellular volume, 30.2%) in both sequences. Altered T1 mapping values are also shown in the remote myocardium, indicating a poor prognosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Acute MI of the right coronary artery territory with right ventricle involvement in a 46-year-old man with atypical chest pain (same patient as in Fig 6). Short-axis LGE MR image shows an MI transmurally involving the inferior and inferoseptal midventricular segments of the LV (thick arrow) (right coronary artery territory). Associated enhancement of the inferior and lateral midventricular wall of the right ventricle is shown (thin arrow) and is secondary to an associated right ventricular MI, which is a condition more commonly associated with inferior MIs of the LV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig13.jpeg" height="1180" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Acute MI of the right coronary artery territory with right ventricle involvement in a 46-year-old man with atypical chest pain (same patient as in <a href="#fig6a">Fig 6</a>). Short-axis LGE MR image shows an MI transmurally involving the inferior and inferoseptal midventricular segments of the LV (thick arrow) (right coronary artery territory). Associated enhancement of the inferior and lateral midventricular wall of the right ventricle is shown (thin arrow) and is secondary to an associated right ventricular MI, which is a condition more commonly associated with inferior MIs of the LV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Previous MI in the left anterior descending coronary artery in a 47-year-old man. LGE MR image shows a two-chamber apical intracavitary thrombus as a focal mass without significant enhancement that is associated with a dyskinetic LV apex (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig14.jpeg" height="1115" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Previous MI in the left anterior descending coronary artery in a 47-year-old man. LGE MR image shows a two-chamber apical intracavitary thrombus as a focal mass without significant enhancement that is associated with a dyskinetic LV apex (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic" aria-label="Classic and modified Lake Louise Criteria, including parametric mapping, in a 41-year-old man with chest pain, transitory ST segment elevation, and right bundle cardiac blockade. Classic Lake Louise Criteria: (a, b) Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR (a) and LGE (b) MR images show myocardial edema and LGE of the right ventricle anterior and free wall (arrow) and enhancement of the right ventricular myocardium and adjacent pericardium. Modified Lake Louise Criteria II: (c) T2 map shows increased T2 values (arrow) in the right ventricular free wall (T2 = 81.1 msec ± 9.98) compared with those of the normal myocardium (T2 = 39.3 msec ± 3.53). (d, e) Native T1 maps show altered T1 values (native T1 = 1326 msec ± 56.6) and increased extracellular volumes (enhanced T1 = 618 msec ± 21.6; extracellular volume, 37.4%) in the right ventricular free wall (arrow), which suggests acute right ventricular myopericarditis. Native T1 mapping is superior to T2-weighted MRI and equivalent to LGE MRI for detection of myocardial edema and is an alternative when there are contraindications to the use of gadolinium-based contrast media. Extracellular volume is a marker of severity in acute and subacute myocarditis. The combination of extracellular volume and LGE improves the diagnostic accuracy compared with the classic Lake Louise Criteria."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig15a.jpeg" height="1023" width="1894" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Classic and modified Lake Louise Criteria, including parametric mapping, in a 41-year-old man with chest pain, transitory ST segment elevation, and right bundle cardiac blockade. Classic Lake Louise Criteria: <b>(a, b)</b> Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR <b>(a)</b> and LGE <b>(b)</b> MR images show myocardial edema and LGE of the right ventricle anterior and free wall (arrow) and enhancement of the right ventricular myocardium and adjacent pericardium. Modified Lake Louise Criteria II: <b>(c)</b> T2 map shows increased T2 values (arrow) in the right ventricular free wall (T2 = 81.1 msec ± 9.98) compared with those of the normal myocardium (T2 = 39.3 msec ± 3.53). <b>(d</b>, <b>e)</b> Native T1 maps show altered T1 values (native T1 = 1326 msec ± 56.6) and increased extracellular volumes (enhanced T1 = 618 msec ± 21.6; extracellular volume, 37.4%) in the right ventricular free wall (arrow), which suggests acute right ventricular myopericarditis. Native T1 mapping is superior to T2-weighted MRI and equivalent to LGE MRI for detection of myocardial edema and is an alternative when there are contraindications to the use of gadolinium-based contrast media. Extracellular volume is a marker of severity in acute and subacute myocarditis. The combination of extracellular volume and LGE improves the diagnostic accuracy compared with the classic Lake Louise Criteria.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="Classic and modified Lake Louise Criteria, including parametric mapping, in a 41-year-old man with chest pain, transitory ST segment elevation, and right bundle cardiac blockade. Classic Lake Louise Criteria: (a, b) Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR (a) and LGE (b) MR images show myocardial edema and LGE of the right ventricle anterior and free wall (arrow) and enhancement of the right ventricular myocardium and adjacent pericardium. Modified Lake Louise Criteria II: (c) T2 map shows increased T2 values (arrow) in the right ventricular free wall (T2 = 81.1 msec ± 9.98) compared with those of the normal myocardium (T2 = 39.3 msec ± 3.53). (d, e) Native T1 maps show altered T1 values (native T1 = 1326 msec ± 56.6) and increased extracellular volumes (enhanced T1 = 618 msec ± 21.6; extracellular volume, 37.4%) in the right ventricular free wall (arrow), which suggests acute right ventricular myopericarditis. Native T1 mapping is superior to T2-weighted MRI and equivalent to LGE MRI for detection of myocardial edema and is an alternative when there are contraindications to the use of gadolinium-based contrast media. Extracellular volume is a marker of severity in acute and subacute myocarditis. The combination of extracellular volume and LGE improves the diagnostic accuracy compared with the classic Lake Louise Criteria."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig15b.jpeg" height="1023" width="1855" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Classic and modified Lake Louise Criteria, including parametric mapping, in a 41-year-old man with chest pain, transitory ST segment elevation, and right bundle cardiac blockade. Classic Lake Louise Criteria: <b>(a, b)</b> Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR <b>(a)</b> and LGE <b>(b)</b> MR images show myocardial edema and LGE of the right ventricle anterior and free wall (arrow) and enhancement of the right ventricular myocardium and adjacent pericardium. Modified Lake Louise Criteria II: <b>(c)</b> T2 map shows increased T2 values (arrow) in the right ventricular free wall (T2 = 81.1 msec ± 9.98) compared with those of the normal myocardium (T2 = 39.3 msec ± 3.53). <b>(d</b>, <b>e)</b> Native T1 maps show altered T1 values (native T1 = 1326 msec ± 56.6) and increased extracellular volumes (enhanced T1 = 618 msec ± 21.6; extracellular volume, 37.4%) in the right ventricular free wall (arrow), which suggests acute right ventricular myopericarditis. Native T1 mapping is superior to T2-weighted MRI and equivalent to LGE MRI for detection of myocardial edema and is an alternative when there are contraindications to the use of gadolinium-based contrast media. Extracellular volume is a marker of severity in acute and subacute myocarditis. The combination of extracellular volume and LGE improves the diagnostic accuracy compared with the classic Lake Louise Criteria.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic" aria-label="Classic and modified Lake Louise Criteria, including parametric mapping, in a 41-year-old man with chest pain, transitory ST segment elevation, and right bundle cardiac blockade. Classic Lake Louise Criteria: (a, b) Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR (a) and LGE (b) MR images show myocardial edema and LGE of the right ventricle anterior and free wall (arrow) and enhancement of the right ventricular myocardium and adjacent pericardium. Modified Lake Louise Criteria II: (c) T2 map shows increased T2 values (arrow) in the right ventricular free wall (T2 = 81.1 msec ± 9.98) compared with those of the normal myocardium (T2 = 39.3 msec ± 3.53). (d, e) Native T1 maps show altered T1 values (native T1 = 1326 msec ± 56.6) and increased extracellular volumes (enhanced T1 = 618 msec ± 21.6; extracellular volume, 37.4%) in the right ventricular free wall (arrow), which suggests acute right ventricular myopericarditis. Native T1 mapping is superior to T2-weighted MRI and equivalent to LGE MRI for detection of myocardial edema and is an alternative when there are contraindications to the use of gadolinium-based contrast media. Extracellular volume is a marker of severity in acute and subacute myocarditis. The combination of extracellular volume and LGE improves the diagnostic accuracy compared with the classic Lake Louise Criteria."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig15c.jpeg" height="1011" width="1292" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. Classic and modified Lake Louise Criteria, including parametric mapping, in a 41-year-old man with chest pain, transitory ST segment elevation, and right bundle cardiac blockade. Classic Lake Louise Criteria: <b>(a, b)</b> Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR <b>(a)</b> and LGE <b>(b)</b> MR images show myocardial edema and LGE of the right ventricle anterior and free wall (arrow) and enhancement of the right ventricular myocardium and adjacent pericardium. Modified Lake Louise Criteria II: <b>(c)</b> T2 map shows increased T2 values (arrow) in the right ventricular free wall (T2 = 81.1 msec ± 9.98) compared with those of the normal myocardium (T2 = 39.3 msec ± 3.53). <b>(d</b>, <b>e)</b> Native T1 maps show altered T1 values (native T1 = 1326 msec ± 56.6) and increased extracellular volumes (enhanced T1 = 618 msec ± 21.6; extracellular volume, 37.4%) in the right ventricular free wall (arrow), which suggests acute right ventricular myopericarditis. Native T1 mapping is superior to T2-weighted MRI and equivalent to LGE MRI for detection of myocardial edema and is an alternative when there are contraindications to the use of gadolinium-based contrast media. Extracellular volume is a marker of severity in acute and subacute myocarditis. The combination of extracellular volume and LGE improves the diagnostic accuracy compared with the classic Lake Louise Criteria.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic" aria-label="Classic and modified Lake Louise Criteria, including parametric mapping, in a 41-year-old man with chest pain, transitory ST segment elevation, and right bundle cardiac blockade. Classic Lake Louise Criteria: (a, b) Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR (a) and LGE (b) MR images show myocardial edema and LGE of the right ventricle anterior and free wall (arrow) and enhancement of the right ventricular myocardium and adjacent pericardium. Modified Lake Louise Criteria II: (c) T2 map shows increased T2 values (arrow) in the right ventricular free wall (T2 = 81.1 msec ± 9.98) compared with those of the normal myocardium (T2 = 39.3 msec ± 3.53). (d, e) Native T1 maps show altered T1 values (native T1 = 1326 msec ± 56.6) and increased extracellular volumes (enhanced T1 = 618 msec ± 21.6; extracellular volume, 37.4%) in the right ventricular free wall (arrow), which suggests acute right ventricular myopericarditis. Native T1 mapping is superior to T2-weighted MRI and equivalent to LGE MRI for detection of myocardial edema and is an alternative when there are contraindications to the use of gadolinium-based contrast media. Extracellular volume is a marker of severity in acute and subacute myocarditis. The combination of extracellular volume and LGE improves the diagnostic accuracy compared with the classic Lake Louise Criteria."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig15d.jpeg" height="1011" width="1206" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span>. Classic and modified Lake Louise Criteria, including parametric mapping, in a 41-year-old man with chest pain, transitory ST segment elevation, and right bundle cardiac blockade. Classic Lake Louise Criteria: <b>(a, b)</b> Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR <b>(a)</b> and LGE <b>(b)</b> MR images show myocardial edema and LGE of the right ventricle anterior and free wall (arrow) and enhancement of the right ventricular myocardium and adjacent pericardium. Modified Lake Louise Criteria II: <b>(c)</b> T2 map shows increased T2 values (arrow) in the right ventricular free wall (T2 = 81.1 msec ± 9.98) compared with those of the normal myocardium (T2 = 39.3 msec ± 3.53). <b>(d</b>, <b>e)</b> Native T1 maps show altered T1 values (native T1 = 1326 msec ± 56.6) and increased extracellular volumes (enhanced T1 = 618 msec ± 21.6; extracellular volume, 37.4%) in the right ventricular free wall (arrow), which suggests acute right ventricular myopericarditis. Native T1 mapping is superior to T2-weighted MRI and equivalent to LGE MRI for detection of myocardial edema and is an alternative when there are contraindications to the use of gadolinium-based contrast media. Extracellular volume is a marker of severity in acute and subacute myocarditis. The combination of extracellular volume and LGE improves the diagnostic accuracy compared with the classic Lake Louise Criteria.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15e" class="graphic" aria-label="Classic and modified Lake Louise Criteria, including parametric mapping, in a 41-year-old man with chest pain, transitory ST segment elevation, and right bundle cardiac blockade. Classic Lake Louise Criteria: (a, b) Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR (a) and LGE (b) MR images show myocardial edema and LGE of the right ventricle anterior and free wall (arrow) and enhancement of the right ventricular myocardium and adjacent pericardium. Modified Lake Louise Criteria II: (c) T2 map shows increased T2 values (arrow) in the right ventricular free wall (T2 = 81.1 msec ± 9.98) compared with those of the normal myocardium (T2 = 39.3 msec ± 3.53). (d, e) Native T1 maps show altered T1 values (native T1 = 1326 msec ± 56.6) and increased extracellular volumes (enhanced T1 = 618 msec ± 21.6; extracellular volume, 37.4%) in the right ventricular free wall (arrow), which suggests acute right ventricular myopericarditis. Native T1 mapping is superior to T2-weighted MRI and equivalent to LGE MRI for detection of myocardial edema and is an alternative when there are contraindications to the use of gadolinium-based contrast media. Extracellular volume is a marker of severity in acute and subacute myocarditis. The combination of extracellular volume and LGE improves the diagnostic accuracy compared with the classic Lake Louise Criteria."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig15e.jpeg" height="1011" width="1202" aria-labelledby="fig15e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15e</span>. Classic and modified Lake Louise Criteria, including parametric mapping, in a 41-year-old man with chest pain, transitory ST segment elevation, and right bundle cardiac blockade. Classic Lake Louise Criteria: <b>(a, b)</b> Midventricular short-axis T2-weighted STIR <b>(a)</b> and LGE <b>(b)</b> MR images show myocardial edema and LGE of the right ventricle anterior and free wall (arrow) and enhancement of the right ventricular myocardium and adjacent pericardium. Modified Lake Louise Criteria II: <b>(c)</b> T2 map shows increased T2 values (arrow) in the right ventricular free wall (T2 = 81.1 msec ± 9.98) compared with those of the normal myocardium (T2 = 39.3 msec ± 3.53). <b>(d</b>, <b>e)</b> Native T1 maps show altered T1 values (native T1 = 1326 msec ± 56.6) and increased extracellular volumes (enhanced T1 = 618 msec ± 21.6; extracellular volume, 37.4%) in the right ventricular free wall (arrow), which suggests acute right ventricular myopericarditis. Native T1 mapping is superior to T2-weighted MRI and equivalent to LGE MRI for detection of myocardial edema and is an alternative when there are contraindications to the use of gadolinium-based contrast media. Extracellular volume is a marker of severity in acute and subacute myocarditis. The combination of extracellular volume and LGE improves the diagnostic accuracy compared with the classic Lake Louise Criteria.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig15e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic" aria-label="Midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old woman (see also Movie 5) with chest pain and suspicion of anterior apical necrosis. (a–c) Retrospective electrocardiographically gated coronary CT angiographic curved multiplanar reformation images show no significant stenosis in the right (a), left circumflex (b), and left anterior descending (c) coronary arteries. (d) Volumetric visual wall motion analysis of coronary CT angiography shows midventricular dyskinesia (thick arrow), with basal and apical hyperkinesia (thin arrows). (e) Vertical long-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows myocardial edema with a noncoronary artery distribution that involves the dyskinetic midventricular segments (arrows). The findings are consistent with a midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig16a.jpeg" height="870" width="1763" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old woman (see also Movie 5) with chest pain and suspicion of anterior apical necrosis. <b>(a</b>–<b>c)</b> Retrospective electrocardiographically gated coronary CT angiographic curved multiplanar reformation images show no significant stenosis in the right <b>(a)</b>, left circumflex <b>(b)</b>, and left anterior descending <b>(c)</b> coronary arteries. <b>(d)</b> Volumetric visual wall motion analysis of coronary CT angiography shows midventricular dyskinesia (thick arrow), with basal and apical hyperkinesia (thin arrows). <b>(e)</b> Vertical long-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows myocardial edema with a noncoronary artery distribution that involves the dyskinetic midventricular segments (arrows). The findings are consistent with a midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old woman (see also Movie 5) with chest pain and suspicion of anterior apical necrosis. (a–c) Retrospective electrocardiographically gated coronary CT angiographic curved multiplanar reformation images show no significant stenosis in the right (a), left circumflex (b), and left anterior descending (c) coronary arteries. (d) Volumetric visual wall motion analysis of coronary CT angiography shows midventricular dyskinesia (thick arrow), with basal and apical hyperkinesia (thin arrows). (e) Vertical long-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows myocardial edema with a noncoronary artery distribution that involves the dyskinetic midventricular segments (arrows). The findings are consistent with a midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig16b.jpeg" height="864" width="1763" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old woman (see also Movie 5) with chest pain and suspicion of anterior apical necrosis. <b>(a</b>–<b>c)</b> Retrospective electrocardiographically gated coronary CT angiographic curved multiplanar reformation images show no significant stenosis in the right <b>(a)</b>, left circumflex <b>(b)</b>, and left anterior descending <b>(c)</b> coronary arteries. <b>(d)</b> Volumetric visual wall motion analysis of coronary CT angiography shows midventricular dyskinesia (thick arrow), with basal and apical hyperkinesia (thin arrows). <b>(e)</b> Vertical long-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows myocardial edema with a noncoronary artery distribution that involves the dyskinetic midventricular segments (arrows). The findings are consistent with a midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic" aria-label="Midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old woman (see also Movie 5) with chest pain and suspicion of anterior apical necrosis. (a–c) Retrospective electrocardiographically gated coronary CT angiographic curved multiplanar reformation images show no significant stenosis in the right (a), left circumflex (b), and left anterior descending (c) coronary arteries. (d) Volumetric visual wall motion analysis of coronary CT angiography shows midventricular dyskinesia (thick arrow), with basal and apical hyperkinesia (thin arrows). (e) Vertical long-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows myocardial edema with a noncoronary artery distribution that involves the dyskinetic midventricular segments (arrows). The findings are consistent with a midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig16c.jpeg" height="860" width="1763" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. Midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old woman (see also Movie 5) with chest pain and suspicion of anterior apical necrosis. <b>(a</b>–<b>c)</b> Retrospective electrocardiographically gated coronary CT angiographic curved multiplanar reformation images show no significant stenosis in the right <b>(a)</b>, left circumflex <b>(b)</b>, and left anterior descending <b>(c)</b> coronary arteries. <b>(d)</b> Volumetric visual wall motion analysis of coronary CT angiography shows midventricular dyskinesia (thick arrow), with basal and apical hyperkinesia (thin arrows). <b>(e)</b> Vertical long-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows myocardial edema with a noncoronary artery distribution that involves the dyskinetic midventricular segments (arrows). The findings are consistent with a midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16d" class="graphic" aria-label="Midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old woman (see also Movie 5) with chest pain and suspicion of anterior apical necrosis. (a–c) Retrospective electrocardiographically gated coronary CT angiographic curved multiplanar reformation images show no significant stenosis in the right (a), left circumflex (b), and left anterior descending (c) coronary arteries. (d) Volumetric visual wall motion analysis of coronary CT angiography shows midventricular dyskinesia (thick arrow), with basal and apical hyperkinesia (thin arrows). (e) Vertical long-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows myocardial edema with a noncoronary artery distribution that involves the dyskinetic midventricular segments (arrows). The findings are consistent with a midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig16d.jpeg" height="1609" width="1186" aria-labelledby="fig16d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span>. Midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old woman (see also Movie 5) with chest pain and suspicion of anterior apical necrosis. <b>(a</b>–<b>c)</b> Retrospective electrocardiographically gated coronary CT angiographic curved multiplanar reformation images show no significant stenosis in the right <b>(a)</b>, left circumflex <b>(b)</b>, and left anterior descending <b>(c)</b> coronary arteries. <b>(d)</b> Volumetric visual wall motion analysis of coronary CT angiography shows midventricular dyskinesia (thick arrow), with basal and apical hyperkinesia (thin arrows). <b>(e)</b> Vertical long-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows myocardial edema with a noncoronary artery distribution that involves the dyskinetic midventricular segments (arrows). The findings are consistent with a midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig16d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16e" class="graphic" aria-label="Midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old woman (see also Movie 5) with chest pain and suspicion of anterior apical necrosis. (a–c) Retrospective electrocardiographically gated coronary CT angiographic curved multiplanar reformation images show no significant stenosis in the right (a), left circumflex (b), and left anterior descending (c) coronary arteries. (d) Volumetric visual wall motion analysis of coronary CT angiography shows midventricular dyskinesia (thick arrow), with basal and apical hyperkinesia (thin arrows). (e) Vertical long-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows myocardial edema with a noncoronary artery distribution that involves the dyskinetic midventricular segments (arrows). The findings are consistent with a midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200084/asset/images/large/rg.2021200084.fig16e.jpeg" height="1132" width="1186" aria-labelledby="fig16e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16e</span>. Midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy in a 43-year-old woman (see also Movie 5) with chest pain and suspicion of anterior apical necrosis. <b>(a</b>–<b>c)</b> Retrospective electrocardiographically gated coronary CT angiographic curved multiplanar reformation images show no significant stenosis in the right <b>(a)</b>, left circumflex <b>(b)</b>, and left anterior descending <b>(c)</b> coronary arteries. <b>(d)</b> Volumetric visual wall motion analysis of coronary CT angiography shows midventricular dyskinesia (thick arrow), with basal and apical hyperkinesia (thin arrows). <b>(e)</b> Vertical long-axis T2-weighted STIR MR image shows myocardial edema with a noncoronary artery distribution that involves the dyskinetic midventricular segments (arrows). The findings are consistent with a midventricular variant of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200084&amp;id=fig16e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Curfman G. Acute Chest Pain in the Emergency Department. <em>JAMA Intern Med</em> 2018;178(2):220.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jamainternmed.2017.7519">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29138793/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Acute+Chest+Pain+in+the+Emergency+Department&amp;author=G.+Curfman&amp;publication_year=2018&amp;journal=JAMA+Intern+Med&amp;pages=220&amp;doi=10.1001%2Fjamainternmed.2017.7519&amp;pmid=29138793">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Schwitter J, Arai AE. Assessment of cardiac ischaemia and viability: role of cardiovascular magnetic resonance. <em>Eur Heart J</em> 2011;32(7):799–809.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1093/eurheartj/ehq481">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21398645/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Assessment+of+cardiac+ischaemia+and+viability%3A+role+of+cardiovascular+magnetic+resonance&amp;author=J+Schwitter&amp;author=AE+Arai&amp;publication_year=2011&amp;journal=Eur+Heart+J&amp;pages=799-809&amp;doi=10.1093%2Feurheartj%2Fehq481&amp;pmid=21398645">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Thygesen K, Alpert JS, Jaffe AS, et al. Third universal definition of myocardial infarction. <em>J Am Coll Cardiol</em> 2012;60(16):1581–1598.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://